1. Executive Summary
1.1 Project Overview
This document specifies the technical requirements for building a fully-connected knowledge graph from Apple Inc.'s SEC filings using a Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) architecture. The system will ingest 3 years of 10-K and 10-Q filings (FY2022-FY2024), extract entities and relationships using 5 specialized experts, and produce a traversable graph visualized with WebGL.

Primary Success Criteria
The project succeeds when ALL nodes in the graph are connected and the graph is fully traversable from any node to any other node.
- 100% graph connectivity (single connected component)
- Expert accuracy meets or exceeds defined thresholds
- WebGL visualization renders graph with 10,000+ nodes at 60fps
- All Apple 10-K and 10-Q filings (2022-2024) successfully processed

1.2 Scope
In Scope
- Apple 10-K filings (FY2022, FY2023, FY2024)
- Apple 10-Q filings (12 quarters)
- 5 MoE experts with accuracy benchmarks
- WebGL graph visualization (Sigma.js)
- Expert accuracy evaluation framework
- Connectivity verification system

Out of Scope
- Other companies' filings
- Real-time filing updates
- Question-answering system
- Production deployment
- Mobile visualization
- Multi-tenant support


2. Related Work
2.1 Financial Knowledge Graphs
This project builds upon existing work in financial knowledge graph construction:

- FinKG (Financial Knowledge Graph): Large-scale knowledge graph for financial domain entities and relationships. Our approach differs by focusing on document-level extraction from SEC filings rather than cross-document entity linking.

- SEC-BERT and FinBERT: Domain-specific language models pre-trained on financial text. We leverage FinBERT (ProsusAI/finbert) for embedding generation, which has shown superior performance on financial NLP tasks compared to general-purpose models.

- Edgar-Corpus: Prior work on processing SEC EDGAR filings for NLP tasks. We extend this by building structured knowledge graphs rather than flat text corpora.

2.2 Mixture-of-Experts Architectures
- Shazeer et al. (2017) - "Outrageously Large Neural Networks": Introduced sparse MoE layers for scaling neural networks. Our architecture adapts this concept to graph construction with specialized experts for different relationship types.

- Switch Transformer (Fedus et al., 2021): Demonstrated efficient routing in MoE systems. While we don't use learned routing, our expert specialization follows similar principles of task decomposition.

- Task-Specific Experts: Unlike traditional MoE where experts are learned, our experts are designed with explicit algorithms for specific relationship types (causal, temporal, semantic).

2.3 Graph Connectivity
- Graph connectivity algorithms (Tarjan's algorithm, Union-Find) form the basis of our connectivity verification.

- Minimum Spanning Tree approaches inspire our bridge insertion strategy for ensuring full connectivity.

- Force-directed layouts (Fruchterman-Reingold) are used in Sigma.js for graph visualization.


