C. Annotation Guidelines
C.1 General Principles
- Annotate based on the text content, not external knowledge
- When uncertain, mark as negative (conservative approach)
- Each edge should have clear textual evidence
- Consider directionality: source -> target

C.2 Cross-Reference Annotations
Positive Examples:
- "As discussed in Note 3..." -> Note 3 node (REFERS_TO)
- "See Item 7 for details" -> Item 7 section (REFERS_TO)
- "The following table summarizes..." -> Adjacent table (EXPLAINS)

Negative Examples:
- Generic phrases without specific targets: "as noted above"
- References to external documents not in corpus
- Ambiguous references that could match multiple targets

C.3 Causal Annotations
Positive Examples:
- "Revenue increased due to higher iPhone sales" (CAUSED_BY)
- "Cost reductions led to improved margins" (LEADS_TO)
- "The decline was driven by supply constraints" (CAUSED_BY)

Negative Examples:
- Temporal co-occurrence without causation: "Revenue grew and costs fell"
- Hypothetical causation: "If sales increase, profits would rise"
- Correlation without clear causal language

C.4 Temporal Annotations
Positive Examples:
- Same XBRL tag across FY2023 -> FY2024 (TEMPORAL_NEXT)
- Same risk factor topic in Q1 -> Q2 (TEMPORAL_NEXT)
- Same entity mentioned in consecutive filings

Negative Examples:
- Similar but distinct concepts across time
- Different granularity (annual vs quarterly) without clear match

C.5 Table-Text Annotations
Positive Examples:
- MD&A paragraph explaining revenue table row (EXPLAINS_LINE_ITEM)
- Note text discussing balance sheet item (EXPLAINS_LINE_ITEM)
- General discussion of table content (DISCUSSES)

Negative Examples:
- Text mentions similar topic but different numbers
- Generic financial discussion without specific table reference

C.6 Semantic Similarity Annotations
Score	Definition
5	Near-identical content (paraphrase)
4	Same topic, same specific details
3	Same topic, different details
2	Related topic
1	Unrelated

Threshold for SEMANTICALLY_SIMILAR edge: Score >= 4

